{
  "texts": [
    "10.3389/fmed.2023.1302844 Frontiers in Medicine 10 frontiersin.org hospital LOS from a multimorbidity network (MN) of older patients, an eigenvector centrality (EVC) score for patients obtained by summing the EVC of their disease nodes was an important factor in predicting LOS, improving the R 2 by 18.7% beyond patient clinical and demographic data (59).",
    "In a DCN with 120 communities including nine major disease groups, EVC scores improved overall accuracy, sensitivity, and specificity, which were 69.52, 78.81, and 69.02%, respectively, for predicting high-cost patients (32).",
    "Degree centrality, eigenvector centrality, closeness centrality, betweenness centrality, and the clustering coefficient, from separate unipartite patient-patient and disease-disease networks, together considerably improved prediction accuracy for diabetes (AUC = 0.911) (35).",
    "Eigenvector centrality (measuring patient influence in the network), closeness centrality (measuring the closeness to other patients), and age had the highest Gini feature importance.",
    "It is also informative to describe a network using graph parameters that capture the overall size, topology, and complexity of the network."
  ]
}